04592nam a22007455i 9780228009436DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280094367 a10.1515/97802280094362doi  a(DE-B1597)655963  a(OCoLC)1263613935  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV9347.A5 7aLAW0260202bisacsh04a364.6/82231 aGacek, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPortable Prisons :bElectronic Monitoring and the Creation of Carceral Territory /cJames Gacek. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTracking Lives and Territories in the Carceral Age -- tConceiving the “Carceral” -- tA Case for Carceral Territory -- tObserving the National Electronic Monitoring Centre -- tOn the Move with G4S Scotland -- tTalking Territorially -- tTaking Back Territory -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe pervasiveness of surveillance, punishment, and control within and outside of spaces such as jails, prisons, and detention centres suggests that the carceral is becoming an increasingly prevalent presence in our lives, going beyond historical standards. The contemporary use of electronic monitoring extends carceral territory beyond prison walls, into people’s homes and everyday lives.Empirically and empathetically driven, Portable Prisons is a telling exploration of the electronic monitoring of offenders based on an ethnographic case study from Scotland. Electronic monitoring must be understood – in both intent and effect – as a carceral practice, an expression of the carceral state and its overreaching punitive capabilities. James Gacek demonstrates that various people experience punishment by means of restrictions around mobility, space, and time in ways that strongly overlap with the reported experiences of interviewed prisoners. Drawing attention to how the neoliberal state outsources the labour of punishment to private corporations and the punished themselves, he also rejects the idea that “soft” punishment is in any way related to the movement for decarceration.Offering an original contribution to our understanding of the geography of incarceration, Portable Prisons is a sophisticated account of electronic monitoring, underlining the growing significance of this field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic monitoring of parolees and probationerszScotlandvCase studies. 0aElectronic surveillancezScotlandvCase studies. 0aElectronic surveillance. 0aImprisonmentzScotlandvCase studies. 0aImprisonment. 0aSocial controlzScotlandvCase studies. 0aSocial control. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / Sentencing.2bisacsh  aScotland.  acarceral.  acriminal justice.  acriminology.  aelectronic monitoring.  ageography.  aplace.  apolitics.  apunishment.  asociology.  aspace.  asurveillance.  aterritory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800943640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228009436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228009436/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles